[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Such examples may arouse suspicions of being generated by a different mechanism, or appear inconsistent with the remainder of that set of data.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection finds application in many domains including cybersecurity, medicine, machine vision, statistics, neuroscience, law enforcement and financial fraud to name only a few.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomalies were initially searched for clear rejection or omission from the data to aid statistical analysis, for example to compute the mean or standard deviation.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] They were also removed to better predictions from models such as linear regression, and more recently their removal aids the performance of machine learning algorithms.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] However, in many applications anomalies themselves are of interest and are the observations most desirous in the entire data set, which need to be identified and separated from noise or irrelevant outliers.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Many attempts have been made in the statistical and computer science communities to define an anomaly.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The concept of intrusion detection, a critical component of anomaly detection, has evolved significantly over time.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Initially, it was a manual process where system administrators would monitor for unusual activities, such as a vacationing user's account being accessed or unexpected printer activity.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] This approach was not scalable and was soon superseded by the analysis of audit logs and system logs for signs of malicious behavior.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] By the late 1970s and early 1980s, the analysis of these logs was primarily used retrospectively to investigate incidents, as the volume of data made it impractical for real-time monitoring.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The affordability of digital storage eventually led to audit logs being analyzed online, with specialized programs being developed to sift through the data.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] These programs, however, were typically run during off-peak hours due to their computational intensity.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The 1990s brought the advent of real-time intrusion detection systems capable of analyzing audit data as it was generated, allowing for immediate detection of and response to attacks.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] This marked a significant shift towards proactive intrusion detection.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] As the field has continued to develop, the focus has shifted to creating solutions that can be efficiently implemented across large and complex network environments, adapting to the ever-growing variety of security threats and the dynamic nature of modern computing infrastructures.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is applicable in a very large number and variety of domains, and is an important subarea of unsupervised machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] As such it has applications in cyber-security, intrusion detection, fraud detection, fault detection, system health monitoring, event detection in sensor networks, detecting ecosystem disturbances, defect detection in images using machine vision, medical diagnosis and law enforcement.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection was proposed for intrusion detection systems (IDS) by Dorothy Denning in 1986.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection for IDS is normally accomplished with thresholds and statistics, but can also be done with soft computing, and inductive learning.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Types of features proposed by 1999 included profiles of users, workstations, networks, remote hosts, groups of users, and programs based on frequencies, means, variances, covariances, and standard deviations.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The counterpart of anomaly detection in intrusion detection is misuse detection.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is vital in fintech for fraud prevention.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Preprocessing data to remove anomalies can be an important step in data analysis, and is done for a number of reasons.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Statistics such as the mean and standard deviation are more accurate after the removal of anomalies, and the visualisation of data can also be improved.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] In supervised learning, removing the anomalous data from the dataset often results in a statistically significant increase in accuracy.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection has become increasingly vital in video surveillance to enhance security and safety.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] With the advent of deep learning technologies, methods using Convolutional Neural Networks (CNNs) and Simple Recurrent Units (SRUs) have shown significant promise in identifying unusual activities or behaviors in video data.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] These models can process and analyze extensive video feeds in real-time, recognizing patterns that deviate from the norm, which may indicate potential security threats or safety violations.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] An important aspect for video surveillance is the development of scalable real-time frameworks.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Such pipelines are required for processing multiple video streams with low computational resources.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] In IT infrastructure management, anomaly detection is crucial for ensuring the smooth operation and reliability of services.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] These are complex systems, composed of many interactive elements and large data quantities, requiring methods to process and reduce this data into a human and machine interpretable format.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Techniques like the IT Infrastructure Library (ITIL) and monitoring frameworks are employed to track and manage system performance and user experience.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Detected anomalies can help identify and pre-empt potential performance degradations or system failures, thus maintaining productivity and business process effectiveness.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is critical for the security and efficiency of Internet of Things (IoT) systems.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] It helps in identifying system failures and security breaches in complex networks of IoT devices.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The methods must manage real-time data, diverse device types, and scale effectively.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Garg et al. have introduced a multi-stage anomaly detection framework that improves upon traditional methods by incorporating spatial clustering, density-based clustering, and locality-sensitive hashing.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] This tailored approach is designed to better handle the vast and varied nature of IoT data, thereby enhancing security and operational reliability in smart infrastructure and industrial IoT systems.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Anomaly detection is crucial in the petroleum industry for monitoring critical machinery.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] A 2015 paper proposed a novel segmentation algorithm using support vector machines to analyze sensor data for real-time anomaly detection.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] In the oil and gas sector, anomaly detection is not just crucial for maintenance and safety, but also for environmental protection.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Aljameel et al. propose an advanced machine learning-based model for detecting minor leaks in oil and gas pipelines, a task traditional methods may miss.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Many anomaly detection techniques have been proposed in literature.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The performance of methods usually depend on the data sets.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] For example, some may be suited to detecting local outliers, while others global, and methods have little systematic advantages over another when compared across many data sets.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Almost all algorithms also require the setting of non-intuitive parameters critical for performance, and usually unknown before application.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] The size of bins are key to the effectiveness of this technique but must be determined by the implementer.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] A more sophisticated technique uses kernel functions to approximate the distribution of the normal data.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Instances in low probability areas of the distribution are then considered anomalies.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Quantum machine learning approaches have been investigated for anomaly detection on near-term quantum hardware.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Quantum support vector machines (QSVMs) using quantum kernel methods, such as the ZZFeatureMap, have been applied to classification of normal versus anomalous instances by leveraging high-dimensional quantum feature spaces.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Histogram-based Outlier Score (HBOS) uses value histograms and assumes feature independence for fast predictions.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Dynamic networks, such as those representing financial systems, social media interactions, and transportation infrastructure, are subject to constant change, making anomaly detection within them a complex task.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Unlike static graphs, dynamic networks reflect evolving relationships and states, requiring adaptive techniques for anomaly detection.
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] Many of the methods discussed above only yield an anomaly score prediction, which often can be explained to users as the point being in a region of low data density (or relatively low density compared to the neighbor's densities).
[src:aws-macie/anomaly-detection] In explainable artificial intelligence, the users demand methods with higher explainability.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud computing and storage provide users with the capability to store and process their data in third-party data centers.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Organizations use the cloud in a variety of service models (e.g., SaaS, PaaS, IaaS) and deployment models (private, public, hybrid, and community).
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Security concerns associated with cloud computing are typically divided into issues faced by cloud providers and those faced by their customers.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] The responsibility is shared and is often described in a vendor's "shared responsibility model".
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] The provider must secure its infrastructure, while customers must secure their applications, identities, and configuration settings.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Analyses of large-scale cloud incidents indicate that many breaches result from misconfigurations and long-unremediated exposures rather than solely from zero-day vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] When an organization stores data or hosts applications on the public cloud, it loses physical access to the hardware.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] As a result, potentially sensitive data may be at risk from insider attacks.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] According to a 2010 Cloud Security Alliance report, insider attacks rank among the top threats in cloud computing.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers must ensure that thorough background checks are conducted for employees with physical access to data centers.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] To conserve resources and reduce cost, cloud providers often store multiple customers' data on the same server.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] As a result, one user's private data might be viewable by another without proper isolation.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Providers implement data isolation and logical segregation to mitigate these risks.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] The extensive use of virtualization in cloud infrastructure brings unique security concerns.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Virtualization introduces an additional layer—the hypervisor—that must be secured and correctly configured.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] A compromise of the hypervisor management system can impact an entire data center.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security architecture is effective only if the correct defensive implementations are in place.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] An efficient cloud security architecture should recognize the issues that will arise with security management and follow all the best practices, procedures, and guidelines to ensure a secure cloud environment.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Security management addresses these issues with security controls.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] These controls protect cloud environments and are put in place to safeguard any weaknesses in the system and reduce the effect of an attack.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Administrative mechanisms intended to reduce attacks by informing attackers of consequences.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Controls designed to reduce vulnerabilities and prevent unauthorized access.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Controls that detect and respond to security events.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Includes monitoring, SIEM, IDS/IPS, malware detection.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Controls that reduce the impact of an incident and restore systems.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering is characterized by the security layers, plan, design, programming, and best practices that exist inside a cloud security arrangement.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security engineering requires the composed and visual model (design and UI) to be characterized by the tasks inside the Cloud.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] This cloud security engineering process includes such things as access to the executives, techniques, and controls to ensure applications and information.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] It also includes ways to deal with and keep up with permeability, consistency, danger stance, and by and large security.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Processes for imparting security standards into cloud administrations and activities assume an approach that fulfills consistent guidelines and essential foundation security parts.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Though the idea of cloud computing is not new, organizations are increasingly adopting it because of its flexible scalability, relative trustability, and cost-effectiveness of services.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] However, despite its rapid adoption in some sectors and disciplines, research and statistics indicate that security-related pitfalls remain a major barrier to its full adoption.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] It is generally recommended that information security controls be selected and implemented in proportion to the risks, typically by assessing the threats, vulnerabilities and impacts.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud security concerns can be grouped in various ways; Gartner identified seven, while the Cloud Security Alliance identified twelve areas of concern.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud access security brokers (CASBs) are software that sits between cloud users and cloud applications to provide visibility into cloud application usage, data protection and governance to monitor all activity and enforce security policies.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Any service without a "hardened" environment is considered a "soft" target.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be protected just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] "Data loss or leakage represents 24.6 % and cloud-related malware 3.4 % of threats causing cloud outages".
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Every enterprise will have its own identity management system to control access to information and computing resources.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers either integrate the customer's identity management system into their own infrastructure, using federation or SSO technology or a biometric-based identification system, or provide an identity management system of their own.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service providers physically secure the IT hardware (servers, routers, cables etc.) against unauthorized access, interference, theft, fire, flood etc., and ensure that essential supplies (such as electricity) are sufficiently robust to minimise the possibility of disruption.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Various information security concerns relating to personnel involved in cloud services are typically handled through screening, security-awareness training, and role-based access controls.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Providers ensure that all critical data (credit-card numbers, for example) are masked or encrypted and that only authorised users have access to data in its entirety.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Moreover, digital identities and credentials must be protected as must any data that the provider collects or produces about customer activity in the cloud.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Penetration testing is the process of performing offensive security tests on a system, service, or computer network to find security weaknesses in it.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Since the cloud is a shared environment with other customers or tenants, following penetration-testing rules of engagement step-by-step is a mandatory requirement.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Scanning and penetration-testing from inside or outside the cloud should be authorised by the cloud provider.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Scanning the cloud from outside and inside using free or commercial tools is crucial.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Without a hardened environment, your service is considered a soft target.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Virtual servers should be hardened just like a physical server against data leakage, malware, and exploited vulnerabilities.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Privacy legislation often varies by country.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] By having information stored via the cloud it is difficult to determine under which jurisdiction the data falls.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Trans-border clouds are popular given that the largest companies transcend several countries.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Legal dilemmas from the ambiguity of the cloud refer to how there is a difference in data-sharing law between and inside organisations.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Due to the autonomous nature of the cloud, consumers are often given management interfaces to monitor their databases.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] By having controls in one central location and by having the interface be easily accessible for user convenience, there is a possibility that a single actor could gain access to the cloud's management interface; giving them control over much of the system.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] The cloud's use of resource pooling means memory or storage resources may be recycled to another user.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] It is possible for current users to access information left by previous ones.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud services require internet connectivity and use internet protocols, making them subject to attacks such as man-in-the-middle attacks.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Furthermore, heavy reliance on internet connectivity means service disruptions or outages can cut off users entirely.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] As encryption algorithms age, vulnerabilities arise.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud providers must stay current with encryption standards and transition older systems before they become compromised.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Some advanced encryption algorithms applied to cloud computing increase the protection of privacy.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] In a practice called crypto-shredding, encryption keys can be deleted when data is no longer used.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Attribute-based encryption is a form of public-key encryption in which the user's secret key and the ciphertext depend on attributes (e.g., the country the user lives in, or their subscription type).
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] In such systems, access to decryption depends not simply on identity but on attributes.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Some of the strengths of ABE are that it bypasses the need for explicit key sharing (as in traditional PKI) and identity-based encryption (IBE).
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] However, ABE suffers from key-redistribution complexity: since decryption keys depend on attributes rather than identities, malicious users might leak attribute information, enabling unauthorized access.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] In CP-ABE, the encryptor controls the access policy for the ciphertext.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] The process includes Setup, Encrypt, KeyGen, and Decrypt algorithms; the encryptor defines an access structure that must match a user's attributes before decryption is allowed.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] In KP-ABE, the sender encrypts under a set of attributes, and the user's private key is issued to match a policy describing which ciphertexts they may decrypt.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] KP-ABE shifts access-control responsibility partially to the key-issuer rather than the encryptor.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] While it provides flexibility, the policy disclosure may weaken privacy guarantees.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Fully Homomorphic Encryption allows arbitrary computation on ciphertext without decryption.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] It is emerging as a high-security option for cloud environments, including voting systems.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] While promising, it remains largely experimental.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Searchable encryption enables secure search on encrypted data.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] It has symmetric and public-key variants.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] While it supports functionality over encrypted data, it introduces extra attack surfaces, especially when attribute indexing is involved.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Numerous laws and regulations govern the storage and use of data.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Similar standards exist in other jurisdictions (e.g., Singapore's Multi-Tier Cloud Security Standard).
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Similar laws may apply in different legal jurisdictions and may differ markedly from those in the US.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Cloud service users must often understand the legal and regulatory differences between the jurisdictions.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] For example, data stored by a cloud service provider (CSP) may be located in, say, Singapore and mirrored in the US.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] plans in place to ensure service continuity and data protection.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] In addition to the requirements on customers, data centers used by cloud providers may be subject to additional compliance obligations.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Using a cloud service provider (CSP) can lead to extra security concerns around data jurisdiction since customer or tenant data may not remain in the same location or provider's cloud.
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] These issues are typically addressed in service-level agreements (SLAs).
[src:aws-macie/cloud-computing-security] Legal issues may also include records-keeping requirements in the public sector, where agencies must retain and make available electronic records in a specific fashion.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Data loss incidents (unauthorized disclosure or deletion of sensitive data) may turn into data leak incidents (data breaches) when media containing sensitive information are lost and then acquired by an unauthorized party, including via data theft.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] However, a data leak is possible without losing the data on the originating side.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] There are limitations to the effectiveness of DLP systems in reducing risk of data loss.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Technological means for prevention data loss include standard security measures, advanced/intelligent security measures, access control and encryption, and content-aware DLP systems, although only the latter category is typically referred to as DLP.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Most DLP systems rely on predefined rules to identify and categorize sensitive information.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Standard security measures, such as firewalls, intrusion detection systems (IDSs), and antivirus software, are widely used to guard against both outsider and insider attacks.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Intrusion detection systems identify unauthorized use, misuse, and abuse of computer systems by monitoring for behavior patterns that differ from legitimate users.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Advanced security measures employ machine learning, behavioral analytics, honeypots, temporal reasoning, and activity-based verification to detect abnormal or unauthorized data access patterns.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Machine learning algorithms enable systems to automatically improve through experience, identifying patterns in large datasets to enhance detection capabilities.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Content-aware DLP systems detect and prevent unauthorized attempts to copy, transmit, or publish sensitive data.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems use mechanisms such as exact data matching, structured data fingerprinting, statistical methods, rule-based detection, and contextual analysis.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Network (data in motion) systems operate at egress points and analyze traffic for sensitive information being transmitted in violation of policy.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Next-generation firewalls and intrusion detection systems often support DLP-like capabilities.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Endpoint (data in use) systems monitor user actions on desktops, servers, and devices, enabling controls such as blocking copying, printing, screen capture, or unauthorized email transmission.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud DLP monitors data within cloud services and applies controls to enforce access and usage policies.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Cloud computing provides on-demand network access to shared computing resources, enabling scalable and flexible data protection strategies.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] These systems help maintain compatibility with existing on-premises DLP infrastructure while addressing issues that are unique to cloud environments such as shared responsibility models, multi-cloud data governance, and shadow IT discovery.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Data identification techniques classify information as structured or unstructured.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Roughly 80% of enterprise data is unstructured.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Recent industry guidance describes data classification and policy alignment as foundational elements of effective DLP programs.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Vendors also emphasize the role of integrated DLP, analytics, and automation in modern data protection strategies.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Data distributors may intentionally or unintentionally share data with third parties, after which it is later found in unauthorized locations.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP investigations attempt to determine the source.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP techniques include access controls, encryption, and data retention policies.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Data encryption transforms readable information into an unreadable format to protect confidentiality, ensuring only authorized parties with the proper decryption key can access the original data.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in use" refers to data currently being accessed.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems may monitor and flag unauthorized manipulation or transfer of such data.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] "Data in motion" refers to data traveling across internal or external networks.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP systems monitor and control this flow.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] False positive management remains a significant issue.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Policies that are too broad tend to generate alerts that require manual review which may overwhelm security teams and reduce the overall effectiveness of DLP software.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Privacy and compliance concerns can arise when an organization monitors employees.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Achieving data security in such situations requires a delicate balance between adequate monitoring and taking care that individual privacy rights are not infringed upon.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Evasion techniques exist including steganography, encryption, or manipulation of a file's format that can sometimes circumvent DLP detection methods and require continuous updating of detection software.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] The complexity of DLP policy increases substantially in global organizations due to their greater size and operation in disparate jurisdictions.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] DLP software in these cases must often contend with more diverse regulatory requirements, a broader range of data types, and relatively complex business processes.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] This makes it challenging to achieve consistent enforcement across regions and departments.
[src:aws-macie/data-loss-prevention-software] Relevant information privacy laws include the EU General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), HIPAA in the United States, and the California Consumer Privacy Act.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The main reason to mask data is to protect information that is classified as personally identifiable information, or mission critical data.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] However, the data must remain usable for the purposes of undertaking valid test cycles.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It must also look real and appear consistent.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is more common to have masking applied to data that is represented outside of a corporate production system.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In other words, where data is needed for the purpose of application development, building program extensions and conducting various test cycles.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is common practice in enterprise computing to take data from the production systems to fill the data component, required for these non-production environments.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] However, this practice is not always restricted to non-production environments.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In some organizations, data that appears on terminal screens to call center operators may have masking dynamically applied based on user security permissions (e.g. preventing call center operators from viewing credit card numbers in billing systems).
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The primary concern from a corporate governance perspective is that personnel conducting work in these non-production environments are not always security cleared to operate with the information contained in the production data.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This practice represents a security hole where data can be copied by unauthorized personnel, and security measures associated with standard production level controls can be easily bypassed.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This represents an access point for a data security breach.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The data must undergo enough changes so that it is not obvious that the masked data is from a source of production data.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] For example, it may be common knowledge in an organisation that there are 10 senior managers all earning in excess of $300k.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] If a test environment of the organisation's HR System also includes 10 identities in the same earning-bracket, then other information could be pieced together to reverse-engineer a real-life identity.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Theoretically, if the data is obviously masked or obfuscated, then it would be reasonable for someone intending a data breach to assume that they could reverse engineer identity-data if they had some degree of knowledge of the identities in the production data-set.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Accordingly, data obfuscation or masking of a data-set applies in such a manner as to ensure that identity and sensitive data records are protected - not just the individual data elements in discrete fields and tables.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The masked values may be required to be consistent across multiple databases within an organization when the databases each contain the specific data element being masked.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Additional constraints as mentioned in (1) above may also apply depending on the data element(s) involved.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Where different character sets are used across the databases that need to connect in this scenario, a scheme of converting the original values to a common representation will need to be applied, either by the masking algorithm itself or prior to invoking said algorithm.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Substitution is one of the most effective methods of applying data masking and being able to preserve the authentic look and feel of the data records.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It allows the masking to be performed in such a manner that another authentic-looking value can be substituted for the existing value.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] There are several data field types where this approach provides optimal benefit in disguising the overall data subset as to whether or not it is a masked data set.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] For example, if dealing with source data which contains customer records, real life surname or first name can be randomly substituted from a supplied or customised look up file.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In most cases, the substitution files will need to be fairly extensive so having large substitution datasets as well the ability to apply customized data substitution sets should be a key element of the evaluation criteria for any data masking solution.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The shuffling method is a very common form of data obfuscation.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is similar to the substitution method but it derives the substitution set from the same column of data that is being masked.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In very simple terms, the data is randomly shuffled within the column.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] However, if used in isolation, anyone with any knowledge of the original data can then apply a "what if" scenario to the data set and then piece back together a real identity.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The shuffling method is also open to being reversed if the shuffling algorithm can be deciphered.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Data shuffling overcomes reservations about using perturbed or modified confidential data because it retains all the desirable properties of perturbation while performing better than other masking techniques in both data utility and disclosure risk.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Shuffling, however, has some real strengths in certain areas.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] If for instance, the end of year figures for financial information in a test data base, one can mask the names of the suppliers and then shuffle the value of the accounts throughout the masked database.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is highly unlikely that anyone, even someone with intimate knowledge of the original data could derive a true data record back to its original values.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The numeric variance method is very useful for applying to financial and date driven information fields.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Effectively, a method utilising this manner of masking can still leave a meaningful range in a financial data set such as payroll.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] If the variance applied is around +/- 10% then it is still a very meaningful data set in terms of the ranges of salaries that are paid to the recipients.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The same also applies to the date information.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Encryption is often the most complex approach to solving the data masking problem.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The encryption algorithm often requires that a "key" be applied to view the data based on user rights.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This often sounds like the best solution, but in practice the key may then be given out to personnel without the proper rights to view the data.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This then defeats the purpose of the masking exercise.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Old databases may then get copied with the original credentials of the supplied key and the same uncontrolled problem lives on.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Recently, the problem of encrypting data while preserving the properties of the entities got recognition and a newly acquired interest among the vendors and academia.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] New challenge gave birth to algorithms performing format-preserving encryption.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] These are based on the accepted Advanced Encryption Standard (AES) algorithmic mode recognized by NIST.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Sometimes a very simplistic approach to masking is adopted through applying a null value to a particular field.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The null value approach is really only useful to prevent visibility of the data element.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In almost all cases, it lessens the degree of data integrity that is maintained in the masked data set.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is not a realistic value and will then fail any application logic validation that may have been applied in the front end software that is in the system under test.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It also highlights to anyone that wishes to reverse engineer any of the identity data that data masking has been applied to some degree on the data set.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Character scrambling or masking out of certain fields is also another simplistic yet very effective method of preventing sensitive information to be viewed.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is really an extension of the previous method of nulling out, but there is a greater emphasis on keeping the data real and not fully masked all together.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This is commonly applied to credit card data in production systems.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] For instance, an operator at a call centre might bill an item to a customer's credit card.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] They then quote a billing reference to the card with the last 4 digits of XXXX XXXX xxxx 6789.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] As an operator they can only see the last 4 digits of the card number, but once the billing system passes the customer's details for charging, the full number is revealed to the payment gateway systems.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This system is not very effective for test systems, but it is very useful for the billing scenario detailed above.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] It is also commonly known as a dynamic data masking method.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Additional rules can also be factored into any masking solution regardless of how the masking methods are constructed.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Product agnostic white papers are a good source of information for exploring some of the more common complex requirements for enterprise masking solutions, which include row internal synchronization rules, table internal synchronization rules and table to Table Synchronization Rules.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Data masking is tightly coupled with building test data.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Two major types of data masking are static and on-the-fly data masking.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Static data masking is usually performed on the golden copy of the database, but can also be applied to values in other sources, including files.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Deterministic masking is the process of replacing a value in a column with the same value whether in the same row, the same table, the same database/schema and between instances/servers/database types.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Example: A database has multiple tables, each with a column that has first names.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] With deterministic masking the first name will always be replaced with the same value – “Lynne” will always become “Denise” – wherever “Lynne” may be in the database.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] There are also alternatives to the static data masking that rely on stochastic perturbations of the data that preserve some of the statistical properties of the original data.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Examples of statistical data obfuscation methods include differential privacy and the *DataSifter* method.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] On-the-fly data masking happens in the process of transferring data from environment to environment without data touching the disk on its way.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The same technique is applied to "Dynamic Data Masking" but one record at a time.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This type of data masking is most useful for environments that do continuous deployments as well as for heavily integrated applications.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Organizations that employ continuous deployment or continuous delivery practices do not have the time necessary to create a backup and load it to the golden copy of the database.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Thus, continuously sending smaller subsets (deltas) of masked testing data from production is important.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In heavily integrated applications, developers get feeds from other production systems at the very onset of development and masking of these feeds is either overlooked and not budgeted until later, making organizations non-compliant.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Having on-the-fly data masking in place becomes essential.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is similar to on-the-fly data masking, but it differs in the sense that on-the-fly data masking is about copying data from one source to another source so that the latter can be shared.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Dynamic data masking happens at runtime, dynamically, and on-demand so that there doesn't need to be a second data source where to store the masked data dynamically.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Dynamic data masking enables several scenarios, many of which revolve around strict privacy regulations e.g. the Singapore Monetary Authority or the Privacy regulations in Europe.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Dynamic data masking is attribute-based and policy-driven.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Dynamic data masking can also be used to encrypt or decrypt values on the fly especially when using format-preserving encryption.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Several standards have emerged in recent years to implement dynamic data filtering and masking.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] For instance, XACML policies can be used to mask data inside databases.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Network proxy between the application and the database: Captures the SQL and applies rewrite on the select request.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Database proxy: is a variation of network proxy.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Database proxy is deployed usually between applications/users and the database.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Applications and users are connecting to the database through database security proxy.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] There are no changes to the way applications and users are connecting to the database.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] There is also no need of an agent to be installed on the database server.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The sql queries are rewritten, but when implemented, this type of dynamic data masking also supported within store procedures and database functions.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Network proxy between the end-user and the application: identifying text strings and replacing them.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This method is not applicable for complex applications as it will easily cause corruption when the real-time string replacement is unintentionally applied.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Code changes in the applications & XACML: code changes are usually hard to perform, impossible to maintain and not applicable for packaged applications.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Within the application run-time: By instrumenting the application run-time, policies are defined to rewrite the result set returned from the data sources, while having full visibility to the application user.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This method is the only applicable way to dynamically mask complex applications as it enables control to the data request, data result and user result.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Supported by a browser plugin: In the case of SaaS or local web applications, browser add-ons can be configured to mask data fields corresponding to precise CSS Selectors.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] This can either be accomplished by marking sensitive fields in the application, for example by a HTML class or by finding the right selectors that identify the fields to be obfuscated or masked.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] In latest years, organizations develop their new applications in the cloud more and more often, regardless of whether final applications will be hosted in the cloud or on- premises.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] The cloud solutions as of now allow organizations to use infrastructure as a service, platform as a service, and software as a service.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] There are various modes of creating test data and moving it from on-premises databases to the cloud, or between different environments within the cloud.
[src:aws-macie/data-masking] Dynamic Data Masking becomes even more critical in cloud when customers need to protecting PII data while relying on cloud providers to administer their databases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Statistics and mathematical optimisation methods compose the foundations of machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Data mining is a related field of study, focusing on exploratory data analysis (EDA) through unsupervised learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] From a theoretical viewpoint, probably approximately correct learning provides a mathematical and statistical framework for describing machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Most traditional machine learning and deep learning algorithms can be described as empirical risk minimisation under this framework.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The term *machine learning* was coined in 1959 by Arthur Samuel, an IBM employee and pioneer in the field of computer gaming and artificial intelligence.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The synonym *self-teaching computers* was also used during this time period.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The earliest machine learning program was introduced in the 1950s, when Samuel invented a computer program that calculated the chance of winning in checkers for each side, but the history of machine learning is rooted in decades of efforts to study human cognitive processes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 1949, Canadian psychologist Donald Hebb published the book *The Organization of Behavior*, in which he introduced a theoretical neural structure formed by certain interactions among nerve cells.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The Hebbian theory of neuron interaction set the groundwork for how many machine learning algorithms work, with connected artificial neurons changing the strength of their connections based on data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Other researchers who have studied human cognitive systems contributed to the modern machine learning technologies as well, including Walter Pitts and Warren McCulloch, who proposed the first mathematical model of neural networks including algorithms that mirror human thought processes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] By the early 1960s, an experimental "learning machine" with punched tape memory, called Cybertron, had been developed by Raytheon Company to analyse sonar signals, electrocardiograms, and speech patterns using rudimentary reinforcement learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It was repetitively "trained" by a human operator/teacher to recognise patterns and equipped with a "goof" button to cause it to reevaluate incorrect decisions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A representative book on research into machine learning during the 1960s was Nils Nilsson's book "Learning Machines", dealing mostly with machine learning for pattern classification.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Interest related to pattern recognition continued into the 1970s, as described by Duda and Hart in 1973.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 1981, a report was given on using teaching strategies so that an artificial neural network learns to recognise 40 characters (26 letters, 10 digits, and 4 special symbols) from a computer terminal.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This follows Alan Turing's proposal in his paper "Computing Machinery and Intelligence", in which the question, "Can machines think?", is replaced by asking whether machines can convincingly imitate a human in its responses to human-posed questions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2014 Ian Goodfellow and others introduced generative adversarial networks (GANs) which could produce realistic synthetic data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] By 2016 AlphaGo had won against top human players in Go using reinforcement learning techniques.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] As a scientific endeavour, machine learning grew out of the quest for artificial intelligence (AI).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In the early days of AI as an academic discipline, some researchers were interested in having machines learn from data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] They attempted to approach the problem with various symbolic methods, as well as what were then termed "neural networks"; these were mostly perceptrons and other models that were later found to be reinventions of the generalised linear models of statistics.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic reasoning was also employed, especially in automated medical diagnosis.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] However, an increasing emphasis on the logical, knowledge-based approach caused a rift between AI and machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Probabilistic systems were plagued by theoretical and practical problems of data acquisition and representation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] By 1980, expert systems had come to dominate AI, and statistics was out of favour.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Work on symbolic/knowledge-based learning continued within AI, leading to inductive logic programming (ILP), but the more statistical line of research was now outside the field of AI proper, in pattern recognition and information retrieval.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Neural network research was abandoned by AI and computer science around the same time.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This subfield, termed "connectionism", was continued by researchers from other disciplines, including John Hopfield, David Rumelhart, and Geoffrey Hinton.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Their main success came in the mid-1980s with the reinvention of backpropagation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning (ML), reorganised and recognised as its own field, started to flourish in the 1990s.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The field changed its goal from achieving artificial intelligence to tackling solvable problems of a practical nature.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It shifted focus away from the symbolic approaches it had inherited from AI, and toward methods and models borrowed from statistics, fuzzy logic, and probability theory.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] There is a close connection between machine learning and compression.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A system that predicts the posterior probabilities of a sequence given its entire history can be used for optimal data compression (by using arithmetic coding on the output distribution).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, an optimal compressor can be used for prediction (by finding the symbol that compresses best, given the previous history).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This equivalence has been used as a justification for using data compression as a benchmark for "general intelligence".
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An alternative view can show compression algorithms implicitly map strings into implicit feature space vectors, and compression-based similarity measures compute similarity within these feature spaces.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For each compressor C(.) we define an associated vector space ℵ, such that C(.) maps an input string x, corresponding to the vector norm ||~x||.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An exhaustive examination of the feature spaces underlying all compression algorithms is precluded by space; instead, feature vectors chooses to examine three representative lossless compression methods, LZW, LZ77, and PPM.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] According to AIXI theory, a connection more directly explained in Hutter Prize, the best possible compression of x is the smallest possible software that generates x.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For example, in that model, a zip file's compressed size includes both the zip file and the unzipping software, since you can not unzip it without both, but there may be an even smaller combined form.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Examples of AI-powered audio/video compression software include NVIDIA Maxine, AIVC.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Examples of software that can perform AI-powered image compression include OpenCV, TensorFlow, MATLAB's Image Processing Toolbox (IPT) and High-Fidelity Generative Image Compression.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised machine learning, k-means clustering can be utilized to compress data by grouping similar data points into clusters.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This technique simplifies handling extensive datasets that lack predefined labels and finds widespread use in fields such as image compression.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Data compression aims to reduce the size of data files, enhancing storage efficiency and speeding up data transmission.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] K-means clustering, an unsupervised machine learning algorithm, is employed to partition a dataset into a specified number of clusters, k, each represented by the centroid of its points.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This process condenses extensive datasets into a more compact set of representative points.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Particularly beneficial in image and signal processing, k-means clustering aids in data reduction by replacing groups of data points with their centroids, thereby preserving the core information of the original data while significantly decreasing the required storage space.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Large language models (LLMs) are also efficient lossless data compressors on some data sets, as demonstrated by DeepMind's research with the Chinchilla 70B model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Developed by DeepMind, Chinchilla 70B effectively compressed data, outperforming conventional methods such as Portable Network Graphics (PNG) for images and Free Lossless Audio Codec (FLAC) for audio.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It achieved compression of image and audio data to 43.4% and 16.4% of their original sizes, respectively.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] There is, however, some reason to be concerned that the data set used for testing overlaps the LLM training data set, making it possible that the Chinchilla 70B model is only an efficient compression tool on data it has already been trained on.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Data mining uses many machine learning methods, but with different goals; on the other hand, machine learning also employs data mining methods as "unsupervised learning" or as a preprocessing step to improve learner accuracy.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Evaluated with respect to known knowledge, an uninformed (unsupervised) method will easily be outperformed by other supervised methods, while in a typical KDD task, supervised methods cannot be used due to the unavailability of training data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning also has intimate ties to optimization: Many learning problems are formulated as minimisation of some loss function on a training set of examples.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Loss functions express the discrepancy between the predictions of the model being trained and the actual problem instances (for example, in classification, one wants to assign a label to instances, and models are trained to correctly predict the preassigned labels of a set of examples).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Characterizing the generalisation of various learning algorithms is an active topic of current research, especially for deep learning algorithms.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning and statistics are closely related fields in terms of methods, but distinct in their principal goal: statistics draws population inferences from a sample, while machine learning finds generalisable predictive patterns.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Conventional statistical analyses require the a priori selection of a model most suitable for the study data set.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In addition, only significant or theoretically relevant variables based on previous experience are included for analysis.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, machine learning is not built on a pre-structured model; rather, the data shape the model by detecting underlying patterns.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The more variables (input) used to train the model, the more accurate the ultimate model will be.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Leo Breiman distinguished two statistical modelling paradigms: the data model and the algorithmic model, wherein "algorithmic model" means more or less the machine learning algorithms like Random forest.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Some statisticians have adopted methods from machine learning, producing the field of *statistical learning*.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Analytical and computational techniques derived from deep-rooted physics of disordered systems can be extended to large-scale problems, including machine learning, e.g., to analyse the weight space of deep neural networks.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Statistical physics is thus finding applications in the area of medical diagnostics.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A core objective of a learner is to generalise from its experience.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Generalisation in this context is the ability of a learning machine to perform accurately on new, unseen examples/tasks after having experienced a learning data set.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The training examples come from some generally unknown probability distribution (considered representative of the space of occurrences) and the learner has to build a general model about this space that enables it to produce sufficiently accurate predictions in new cases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The computational analysis of machine learning algorithms and their performance is a branch of theoretical computer science known as computational learning theory.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] One major framework is the probably approximately correct learning model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Because training sets are finite and the future is uncertain, learning theory usually does not yield guarantees of the performance of algorithms.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Instead, probabilistic bounds on the performance are quite common.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The bias–variance decomposition is one way to quantify generalisation error.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For the best performance in the context of generalisation, the complexity of the hypothesis should match the complexity of the function underlying the data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] If the hypothesis is less complex than the function, then the model has underfitted the data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] If the complexity of the model is increased in response, then the training error decreases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] But if the hypothesis is too complex, then the model is subject to overfitting and generalisation will be poorer.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performance bounds, learning theorists study the time complexity and feasibility of learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In computational learning theory, a computation is considered feasible if it can be done in polynomial time.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] There are two kinds of time complexity results: Positive results show that a certain class of functions can be learned in polynomial time.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Negative results show that certain classes cannot be learned in polynomial time.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Although each algorithm has advantages and limitations, no single algorithm works for all problems.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Supervised learning algorithms build a mathematical model of a set of data that contains both the inputs and the desired outputs.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The data, known as training data, consists of a set of training examples.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Each training example has one or more inputs and the desired output, also known as a supervisory signal.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In the mathematical model, each training example is represented by an array or vector, sometimes called a feature vector, and the training data is represented by a matrix.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Through iterative optimisation of an objective function, supervised learning algorithms learn a function that can be used to predict the output associated with new inputs.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An optimal function allows the algorithm to correctly determine the output for inputs that were not a part of the training data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An algorithm that improves the accuracy of its outputs or predictions over time is said to have learned to perform that task.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Types of supervised-learning algorithms include active learning, classification and regression.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Classification algorithms are used when the outputs are restricted to a limited set of values, while regression algorithms are used when the outputs can take any numerical value within a range.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For example, in a classification algorithm that filters emails, the input is an incoming email, and the output is the folder in which to file the email.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In contrast, regression is used for tasks such as predicting a person's height based on factors like age and genetics or forecasting future temperatures based on historical data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Similarity learning is an area of supervised machine learning closely related to regression and classification, but the goal is to learn from examples using a similarity function that measures how similar or related two objects are.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It has applications in ranking, recommendation systems, visual identity tracking, face verification, and speaker verification.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised learning algorithms find structures in data that has not been labelled, classified or categorised.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Instead of responding to feedback, unsupervised learning algorithms identify commonalities in the data and react based on the presence or absence of such commonalities in each new piece of data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Central applications of unsupervised machine learning include clustering, dimensionality reduction, and density estimation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Cluster analysis is the assignment of a set of observations into subsets (called *clusters*) so that observations within the same cluster are similar according to one or more predesignated criteria, while observations drawn from different clusters are dissimilar.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Different clustering techniques make different assumptions on the structure of the data, often defined by some *similarity metric* and evaluated, for example, by *internal compactness*, or the similarity between members of the same cluster, and *separation*, the difference between clusters.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Other methods are based on *estimated density* and *graph connectivity*.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A special type of unsupervised learning called self-supervised learning involves training a model by generating the supervisory signal from the data itself.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Dimensionality reduction is a process of reducing the number of random variables under consideration by obtaining a set of principal variables.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In other words, it is a process of reducing the dimension of the feature set, also called the "number of features".
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Most of the dimensionality reduction techniques can be considered as either feature elimination or extraction.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] One of the popular methods of dimensionality reduction is principal component analysis (PCA).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] PCA involves changing higher-dimensional data (e.g., 3D) to a smaller space (e.g., 2D).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The manifold hypothesis proposes that high-dimensional data sets lie along low-dimensional manifolds, and many dimensionality reduction techniques make this assumption, leading to the areas of manifold learning and manifold regularisation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised learning falls between unsupervised learning (without any labelled training data) and supervised learning (with completely labelled training data).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Some of the training examples are missing training labels, yet many machine-learning researchers have found that unlabelled data, when used in conjunction with a small amount of labelled data, can produce a considerable improvement in learning accuracy.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In weakly supervised learning, the training labels are noisy, limited, or imprecise; however, these labels are often cheaper to obtain, resulting in larger effective training sets.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning is an area of machine learning concerned with how software agents ought to take actions in an environment to maximise some notion of cumulative reward.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Due to its generality, the field is studied in many other disciplines, such as game theory, control theory, operations research, information theory, simulation-based optimisation, multi-agent systems, swarm intelligence, statistics and genetic algorithms.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In reinforcement learning, the environment is typically represented as a Markov decision process (MDP).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Many reinforcement learning algorithms use dynamic programming techniques.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms do not assume knowledge of an exact mathematical model of the MDP and are used when exact models are infeasible.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Reinforcement learning algorithms are used in autonomous vehicles or in learning to play a game against a human opponent.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Other approaches have been developed which do not fit neatly into this three-fold categorisation, and sometimes more than one is used by the same machine learning system.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For example, topic modelling, meta-learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Self-learning, as a machine learning paradigm, was introduced in 1982 along with a neural network capable of self-learning, named *crossbar adaptive array* (CAA).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It gives a solution to the problem learning without any external reward, by introducing emotion as an internal reward.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Emotion is used as a state evaluation of a self-learning agent.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The CAA self-learning algorithm computes, in a crossbar fashion, both decisions about actions and emotions (feelings) about consequence situations.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The system is driven by the interaction between cognition and emotion.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It is a system with only one input, situation, and only one output, action (or behaviour) a.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] There is neither a separate reinforcement input nor an advice input from the environment.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The backpropagated value (secondary reinforcement) is the emotion toward the consequence situation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The CAA exists in two environments, one is the behavioural environment where it behaves, and the other is the genetic environment, wherefrom it initially and only once receives initial emotions about situations to be encountered in the behavioural environment.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] After receiving the genome (species) vector from the genetic environment, the CAA learns a goal-seeking behaviour in an environment that contains both desirable and undesirable situations.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Several learning algorithms aim at discovering better representations of the inputs provided during training.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Classic examples include principal component analysis and cluster analysis.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning algorithms, also called representation learning algorithms, often attempt to preserve the information in their input but also transform it in a way that makes it useful, often as a pre-processing step before performing classification or predictions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This technique allows reconstruction of the inputs coming from the unknown data-generating distribution, while not being necessarily faithful to configurations that are implausible under that distribution.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This replaces manual feature engineering, and allows a machine to both learn the features and use them to perform a specific task.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning can be either supervised or unsupervised.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In supervised feature learning, features are learned using labelled input data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Examples include artificial neural networks, multilayer perceptrons, and supervised dictionary learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In unsupervised feature learning, features are learned with unlabelled input data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Examples include dictionary learning, independent component analysis, autoencoders, matrix factorisation and various forms of clustering.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Manifold learning algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is low-dimensional.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Sparse coding algorithms attempt to do so under the constraint that the learned representation is sparse, meaning that the mathematical model has many zeros.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Multilinear subspace learning algorithms aim to learn low-dimensional representations directly from tensor representations for multidimensional data, without reshaping them into higher-dimensional vectors.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning algorithms discover multiple levels of representation, or a hierarchy of features, with higher-level, more abstract features defined in terms of (or generating) lower-level features.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It has been argued that an intelligent machine learns a representation that disentangles the underlying factors of variation that explain the observed data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Feature learning is motivated by the fact that machine learning tasks such as classification often require input that is mathematically and computationally convenient to process.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] However, real-world data such as images, video, and sensory data have not yielded attempts to algorithmically define specific features.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An alternative is to discover such features or representations through examination, without relying on explicit algorithms.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning is a feature learning method where a training example is represented as a linear combination of basis functions and assumed to be a sparse matrix.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The method is strongly NP-hard and difficult to solve approximately.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A popular heuristic method for sparse dictionary learning is the *k*-SVD algorithm.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has been applied in several contexts.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In classification, the problem is to determine the class to which a previously unseen training example belongs.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For a dictionary where each class has already been built, a new training example is associated with the class that is best sparsely represented by the corresponding dictionary.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Sparse dictionary learning has also been applied in image denoising.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The key idea is that a clean image patch can be sparsely represented by an image dictionary, but the noise cannot.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, anomaly detection, also known as outlier detection, is the identification of rare items, events or observations that raise suspicions by differing significantly from the majority of the data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Typically, the anomalous items represent an issue such as bank fraud, a structural defect, medical problems or errors in a text.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Anomalies are referred to as outliers, novelties, noise, deviations and exceptions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In particular, in the context of abuse and network intrusion detection, the interesting objects are often not rare, but unexpected bursts of inactivity.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This pattern does not adhere to the common statistical definition of an outlier as a rare object.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Many outlier detection methods (in particular, unsupervised algorithms) will fail on such data unless aggregated appropriately.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Instead, a cluster analysis algorithm may be able to detect the micro-clusters formed by these patterns.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Three broad categories of anomaly detection techniques exist.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Unsupervised anomaly detection techniques detect anomalies in an unlabelled test data set under the assumption that the majority of the instances in the data set are normal, by looking for instances that seem to fit the least to the remainder of the data set.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Supervised anomaly detection techniques require a data set that has been labelled as "normal" and "abnormal" and involves training a classifier (the key difference from many other statistical classification problems is the inherently unbalanced nature of outlier detection).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Semi-supervised anomaly detection techniques construct a model representing normal behaviour from a given normal training data set and then test the likelihood of a test instance being generated by the model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Robot learning is inspired by a multitude of machine learning methods, starting from supervised learning, reinforcement learning, and finally meta-learning (e.g.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Association rule learning is a rule-based machine learning method for discovering relationships between variables in large databases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It is intended to identify strong rules discovered in databases using some measure of "interestingness".
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning is a general term for any machine learning method that identifies, learns, or evolves "rules" to store, manipulate or apply knowledge.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The defining characteristic of a rule-based machine learning algorithm is the identification and utilisation of a set of relational rules that collectively represent the knowledge captured by the system.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This is in contrast to other machine learning algorithms that commonly identify a singular model that can be universally applied to any instance in order to make a prediction.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning approaches include learning classifier systems, association rule learning, and artificial immune systems.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Based on the concept of strong rules, Rakesh Agrawal, Tomasz Imieliński and Arun Swami introduced association rules for discovering regularities between products in large-scale transaction data recorded by point-of-sale (POS) systems in supermarkets.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For example, the rule $\{\mathrm {onions,potatoes} \}\Rightarrow \{\mathrm {burger} \}$ found in the sales data of a supermarket would indicate that if a customer buys onions and potatoes together, they are likely to also buy hamburger meat.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Such information can be used as the basis for decisions about marketing activities such as promotional pricing or product placements.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In addition to market basket analysis, association rules are employed today in application areas including Web usage mining, intrusion detection, continuous production, and bioinformatics.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In contrast with sequence mining, association rule learning typically does not consider the order of items either within a transaction or across transactions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Learning classifier systems (LCS) are a family of rule-based machine learning algorithms that combine a discovery component, typically a genetic algorithm, with a learning component, performing either supervised learning, reinforcement learning, or unsupervised learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] They seek to identify a set of context-dependent rules that collectively store and apply knowledge in a piecewise manner to make predictions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming (ILP) is an approach to rule learning using logic programming as a uniform representation for input examples, background knowledge, and hypotheses.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Given an encoding of the known background knowledge and a set of examples represented as a logical database of facts, an ILP system will derive a hypothesized logic program that entails all positive and no negative examples.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Inductive programming is a related field that considers any kind of programming language for representing hypotheses (and not only logic programming), such as functional programs.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Inductive logic programming is particularly useful in bioinformatics and natural language processing.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Gordon Plotkin and Ehud Shapiro laid the initial theoretical foundation for inductive machine learning in a logical setting.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Shapiro built their first implementation (Model Inference System) in 1981: a Prolog program that inductively inferred logic programs from positive and negative examples.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The term *inductive* here refers to philosophical induction, suggesting a theory to explain observed facts, rather than mathematical induction, proving a property for all members of a well-ordered set.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A **machine learning model** is a type of mathematical model that, once "trained" on a given dataset, can be used to make predictions or classifications on new data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] During training, a learning algorithm iteratively adjusts the model's internal parameters to minimise errors in its predictions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] By extension, the term "model" can refer to several levels of specificity, from a general class of models and their associated learning algorithms to a fully trained model with all its internal parameters tuned.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Various types of models have been used and researched for machine learning systems, picking the best model for a task is called model selection.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks (ANNs), or connectionist systems, are computing systems vaguely inspired by the biological neural networks that constitute animal brains.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Such systems "learn" to perform tasks by considering examples, generally without being programmed with any task-specific rules.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An ANN is a model based on a collection of connected units or nodes called "artificial neurons", which loosely model the neurons in a biological brain.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Each connection, like the synapses in a biological brain, can transmit information, a "signal", from one artificial neuron to another.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An artificial neuron that receives a signal can process it and then signal additional artificial neurons connected to it.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In common ANN implementations, the signal at a connection between artificial neurons is a real number, and the output of each artificial neuron is computed by some non-linear function of the sum of its inputs.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The connections between artificial neurons are called "edges".
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons and edges typically have a weight that adjusts as learning proceeds.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The weight increases or decreases the strength of the signal at a connection.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neurons may have a threshold such that the signal is only sent if the aggregate signal crosses that threshold.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Typically, artificial neurons are aggregated into layers.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Different layers may perform different kinds of transformations on their inputs.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Signals travel from the first layer (the input layer) to the last layer (the output layer), possibly after traversing the layers multiple times.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The original goal of the ANN approach was to solve problems in the same way that a human brain would.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] However, over time, attention moved to performing specific tasks, leading to deviations from biology.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Artificial neural networks have been used on a variety of tasks, including computer vision, speech recognition, machine translation, social network filtering, playing board and video games and medical diagnosis.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Deep learning consists of multiple hidden layers in an artificial neural network.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This approach tries to model the way the human brain processes light and sound into vision and hearing.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Some successful applications of deep learning are computer vision and speech recognition.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Decision tree learning uses a decision tree as a predictive model to go from observations about an item (represented in the branches) to conclusions about the item's target value (represented in the leaves).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It is one of the predictive modelling approaches used in statistics, data mining, and machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Tree models where the target variable can take a discrete set of values are called classification trees; in these tree structures, leaves represent class labels, and branches represent conjunctions of features that lead to those class labels.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Decision trees where the target variable can take continuous values (typically real numbers) are called regression trees.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In decision analysis, a decision tree can be used to visually and explicitly represent decisions and decision making.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In data mining, a decision tree describes data, but the resulting classification tree can be an input for decision-making.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Random forest regression (RFR) falls under the umbrella of decision tree-based models.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] RFR is an ensemble learning method that builds multiple decision trees and averages their predictions to improve accuracy and to avoid overfitting.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] To build decision trees, RFR uses bootstrapped sampling; for instance, each decision tree is trained on random data from the training set.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This random selection of RFR for training enables the model to reduce biased predictions and achieve a higher degree of accuracy.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] RFR generates independent decision trees, and it can work on single-output data as well as multiple regressor tasks.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This makes RFR compatible to be use in various applications.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Support-vector machines (SVMs), also known as support-vector networks, are a set of related supervised learning methods used for classification and regression.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of training examples, each marked as belonging to one of two categories, an SVM training algorithm builds a model that predicts whether a new example falls into one category.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] An SVM training algorithm is a non-probabilistic, binary, linear classifier, although methods such as Platt scaling exist to use SVM in a probabilistic classification setting.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In addition to performing linear classification, SVMs can efficiently perform a non-linear classification using what is called the kernel trick, implicitly mapping their inputs into high-dimensional feature spaces.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Regression analysis encompasses a large variety of statistical methods to estimate the relationship between input variables and their associated features.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Its most common form is linear regression, where a single line is drawn to best fit the given data according to a mathematical criterion such as ordinary least squares.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The latter is often extended by regularisation methods to mitigate overfitting and bias, as in ridge regression.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Multivariate linear regression extends the concept of linear regression to handle multiple dependent variables simultaneously.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This approach estimates the relationships between a set of input variables and several output variables by fitting a multidimensional linear model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It is particularly useful in scenarios where outputs are interdependent or share underlying patterns, such as predicting multiple economic indicators or reconstructing images, which are inherently multi-dimensional.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A Bayesian network, belief network, or directed acyclic graphical model is a probabilistic graphical model that represents a set of random variables and their conditional independence with a directed acyclic graph (DAG).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For example, a Bayesian network could represent the probabilistic relationships between diseases and symptoms.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Given symptoms, the network can be used to compute the probabilities of the presence of various diseases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Efficient algorithms exist that perform inference and learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Bayesian networks that model sequences of variables, like speech signals or protein sequences, are called dynamic Bayesian networks.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Generalisations of Bayesian networks that can represent and solve decision problems under uncertainty are called influence diagrams.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A Gaussian process is a stochastic process in which every finite collection of the random variables in the process has a multivariate normal distribution, and it relies on a pre-defined covariance function, or kernel, that models how pairs of points relate to each other depending on their locations.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Given a set of observed points, or input–output examples, the distribution of the (unobserved) output of a new point as a function of its input data can be directly computed by looking at the observed points and the covariances between those points and the new, unobserved point.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Gaussian processes are popular surrogate models in Bayesian optimisation used to do hyperparameter optimisation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A genetic algorithm (GA) is a search algorithm and heuristic technique that mimics the process of natural selection, using methods such as mutation and crossover to generate new genotypes in the hope of finding good solutions to a given problem.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In machine learning, genetic algorithms were used in the 1980s and 1990s.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Conversely, machine learning techniques have been used to improve the performance of genetic and evolutionary algorithms.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] The theory of belief functions, also referred to as evidence theory or Dempster–Shafer theory, is a general framework for reasoning with uncertainty, with understood connections to other frameworks such as probability, possibility and imprecise probability theories.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] These theoretical frameworks can be thought of as a kind of learner and have some analogous properties of how evidence is combined (e.g., Dempster's rule of combination), just like how in a pmf-based Bayesian approach would combine probabilities.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] However, there are many caveats to these beliefs functions when compared to Bayesian approaches to incorporate ignorance and uncertainty quantification.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] However, the computational complexity of these algorithms is dependent on the number of propositions (classes), and can lead to a much higher computation time when compared to other machine learning approaches.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Rule-based machine learning (RBML) is a branch of machine learning that automatically discovers and learns 'rules' from data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] It provides interpretable models, making it useful for decision-making in fields like healthcare, fraud detection, and cybersecurity.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Key RBML techniques includes learning classifier systems, association rule learning, artificial immune systems, and other similar models.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] These methods extract patterns from data and evolve rules over time.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Typically, machine learning models require a high quantity of reliable data to perform accurate predictions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] When training a machine learning model, machine learning engineers need to target and collect a large and representative sample of data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Data from the training set can be as varied as a corpus of text, a collection of images, sensor data, and data collected from individual users of a service.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Overfitting is something to watch out for when training a machine learning model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Trained models derived from biased or non-evaluated data can result in skewed or undesired predictions.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Biased models may result in detrimental outcomes, thereby furthering the negative impacts on society or objectives.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Algorithmic bias is a potential result of data not being fully prepared for training.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning ethics is becoming a field of study and, notably, becoming integrated within machine learning engineering teams.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Federated learning is an adapted form of distributed artificial intelligence to train machine learning models that decentralises the training process, allowing for users' privacy to be maintained by not needing to send their data to a centralised server.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] This also increases efficiency by decentralising the training process to many devices.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] For example, Gboard uses federated machine learning to train search query prediction models on users' mobile phones without having to send individual searches back to Google.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2006, the media-services provider Netflix held the first "Netflix Prize" competition to find a program to better predict user preferences and improve the accuracy of its existing Cinematch movie recommendation algorithm by at least 10%.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] A joint team made up of researchers from AT&T Labs-Research in collaboration with the teams Big Chaos and Pragmatic Theory built an ensemble model to win the Grand Prize in 2009 for $1 million.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Shortly after the prize was awarded, Netflix realised that viewers' ratings were not the best indicators of their viewing patterns ("everything is a recommendation") and they changed their recommendation engine accordingly.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2010, an article in *The Wall Street Journal* noted the use of machine learning by Rebellion Research to predict the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2012, co-founder of Sun Microsystems, Vinod Khosla, predicted that 80% of medical doctors jobs would be lost in the next two decades to automated machine learning medical diagnostic software.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2014, it was reported that a machine learning algorithm had been applied in the field of art history to study fine art paintings and that it may have revealed previously unrecognised influences among artists.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2019 Springer Nature published the first research book created using machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] In 2020, machine learning technology was used to help make diagnoses and aid researchers in developing a cure for COVID-19.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Machine learning was recently applied to predict the pro-environmental behaviour of travellers.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Recently, machine learning technology was also applied to optimise smartphone's performance and thermal behaviour based on the user's interaction with the phone.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] When applied correctly, machine learning algorithms (MLAs) can utilise a wide range of company characteristics to predict stock returns without overfitting.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] By employing effective feature engineering and combining forecasts, MLAs can generate results that far surpass those obtained from basic linear techniques like OLS.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Recent advancements in machine learning have extended into the field of quantum chemistry, where novel algorithms now enable the prediction of solvent effects on chemical reactions, thereby offering new tools for chemists to tailor experimental conditions for optimal outcomes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Machine Learning is becoming a useful tool to investigate and predict evacuation decision-making in large-scale and small-scale disasters.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Different solutions have been tested to predict if and when householders decide to evacuate during wildfires and hurricanes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p01] Other applications have been focusing on pre evacuation decisions in building fires.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Although machine learning has been transformative in some fields, machine-learning programs often fail to deliver expected results.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Reasons for this are numerous: lack of (suitable) data, lack of access to the data, data bias, privacy problems, badly chosen tasks and algorithms, wrong tools and people, lack of resources, and evaluation problems.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] The "black box theory" poses another yet significant challenge.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Black box refers to a situation where the algorithm producing an output is entirely opaque, meaning that even the designers of an application cannot audit the pattern that the machine extracted from the data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] The House of Lords Select Committee, which claimed that such an "intelligence system" that could have a "substantial impact on an individual's life" would not be considered acceptable unless it provided "a full and satisfactory explanation for the decisions" it makes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In 2018, a self-driving car from Uber failed to detect a pedestrian, who was killed after a collision.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Attempts to use machine learning in healthcare with the IBM Watson system failed to deliver even after years of time and billions of dollars invested.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Microsoft's Bing Chat chatbot has been reported to produce hostile and offensive response against its users.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning has been used as a strategy to update the evidence related to a systematic review and increased reviewer burden related to the growth of biomedical literature.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] While it has improved with training sets, it has not yet developed sufficiently to reduce the workload burden without limiting the necessary sensitivity for the findings research itself.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Explainable AI (XAI), or Interpretable AI, or Explainable Machine Learning (XML), is artificial intelligence (AI) in which humans can understand the decisions or predictions made by the AI.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] It contrasts with the "black box" concept in machine learning where even its designers cannot explain why an AI arrived at a specific decision.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] By refining the mental models of users of AI-powered systems and dismantling their misconceptions, XAI promises to help users perform more effectively.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] XAI may be an implementation of the social right to explanation.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Settling on a bad, overly complex theory gerrymandered to fit all the past training data is known as overfitting.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Many systems attempt to reduce overfitting by rewarding a theory in accordance with how well it fits the data but penalising the theory in accordance with how complex the theory is.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] It is unclear to what extent the phenomenon threatens the long-term development of such models, and some techniques have been proposed to mitigate the effect.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] , inconsistent carriage lengths, unnatural amounts of visual noise, and a carriage bending along its length as it rounds the turn.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In the field of artificial intelligence (AI), a hallucination or artificial hallucination (also called bullshitting, confabulation, or delusion) is a response generated by AI that contains false or misleading information presented as fact.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] The term draws a loose analogy with human psychology, where a hallucination typically involves false *percepts*.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] For example, a chatbot powered by large language models (LLMs), like ChatGPT, may embed plausible-sounding random falsehoods within its generated content.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Detecting and mitigating errors and hallucinations pose significant challenges for practical deployment and reliability of LLMs in high-stakes scenarios, such as chip design, supply chain logistics, and medical diagnostics.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Some software engineers and statisticians have criticized the specific term "AI hallucination" for unreasonably anthropomorphizing computers.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Symbolic artificial intelligence models generally do not produce hallucinations, unlike large language models.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Learners can also be disappointed by "learning the wrong lesson".
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] A toy example is that an image classifier trained only on pictures of brown horses and black cats might conclude that all brown patches are likely to be horses.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Modifying these patterns on a legitimate image can result in "adversarial" images that the system misclassifies.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Adversarial vulnerabilities can also result in nonlinear systems or from non-pattern perturbations.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] For some systems, it is possible to change the output by only changing a single adversarially chosen pixel.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Machine learning models are often vulnerable to manipulation or evasion via adversarial machine learning.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Researchers have demonstrated how backdoors can be placed undetectably into classifying (e.g., for categories "spam" and "not spam" of posts) machine learning models that are often developed or trained by third parties.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Parties can change the classification of any input, including in cases for which a type of data/software transparency is provided, possibly including white-box access.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Classification of machine learning models can be validated by accuracy estimation techniques like the holdout method, which splits the data into a training and test set (conventionally 2/3 training set and 1/3 test set designation) and evaluates the performance of the training model on the test set.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In comparison, the K-fold-cross-validation method randomly partitions the data into K subsets and then K experiments are performed each considering 1 subset for evaluation and the remaining K-1 subsets for training the model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In addition to the holdout and cross-validation methods, bootstrap, which samples n instances with replacement from the dataset, can be used to assess model accuracy.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In addition to overall accuracy, investigators frequently report sensitivity and specificity, meaning true positive rate (TPR) and true negative rate (TNR), respectively.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Similarly, investigators sometimes report the false positive rate (FPR) as well as the false negative rate (FNR).
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] However, these rates are ratios that fail to reveal their numerators and denominators.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Receiver operating characteristic (ROC), along with the accompanying Area Under the ROC Curve (AUC), offer additional tools for classification model assessment.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Higher AUC is associated with a better performing model.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] The ethics of artificial intelligence covers a broad range of topics within AI that are considered to have particular ethical stakes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] This includes algorithmic biases, fairness, accountability, transparency, privacy, and regulation, particularly where systems influence or automate human decision-making.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Some application areas may also have particularly important ethical implications, like healthcare, education, criminal justice, or the military.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Different machine learning approaches can suffer from different data biases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] A machine learning system trained specifically on current customers may not be able to predict the needs of new customer groups that are not represented in the training data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] When trained on human-made data, machine learning is likely to pick up the constitutional and unconscious biases already present in society.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Systems that are trained on datasets collected with biases may exhibit these biases upon use (algorithmic bias), thus digitising cultural prejudices.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] For example, in 1988, the UK's Commission for Racial Equality found that St.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] George's Medical School had been using a computer program trained from data of previous admissions staff and this program had denied nearly 60 candidates who were found to either be women or have non-European-sounding names.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Using job hiring data from a firm with racist hiring policies may lead to a machine learning system duplicating the bias by scoring job applicants by similarity to previous successful applicants.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Another example includes predictive policing company Geolitica's predictive algorithm that resulted in "disproportionately high levels of over-policing in low-income and minority communities" after being trained with historical crime data.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In fact, according to research carried out by the Computing Research Association in 2021, "female faculty make up just 16.1%" of all faculty members who focus on AI among several universities around the world.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Furthermore, among the group of "new U.S. resident AI PhD graduates," 45% identified as white, 22.4% as Asian, 3.2% as Hispanic, and 2.4% as African American, which further demonstrates a lack of diversity in the field of AI.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Language models learned from data have been shown to contain human-like biases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Because human languages contain biases, machines trained on language *corpora* will necessarily also learn these biases.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In 2016, Microsoft tested Tay, a chatbot that learned from Twitter, and it quickly picked up racist and sexist language.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In an experiment carried out by ProPublica, an investigative journalism organisation, a machine learning algorithm's insight into the recidivism rates among prisoners falsely flagged "black defendants high risk twice as often as white defendants".
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] In 2015, Google Photos once tagged a couple of black people as gorillas, which caused controversy.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] The gorilla label was subsequently removed, and in 2023, it still cannot recognise gorillas.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Similar issues with recognising non-white people have been found in many other systems.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Because of such challenges, the effective use of machine learning may take longer to be adopted in other domains.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Concern for fairness in machine learning, that is, reducing bias in machine learning and propelling its use for human good, is increasingly expressed by artificial intelligence scientists, including Fei-Fei Li, who said that "[t]here's nothing artificial about AI.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] It's inspired by people, it's created by people, and—most importantly—it impacts people.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] There are concerns among health care professionals that these systems might not be designed in the public's interest but as income-generating machines.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] This is especially true in the United States, where there is a long-standing ethical dilemma of improving health care, but also increasing profits.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] For example, the algorithms could be designed to provide patients with unnecessary tests or medication in which the algorithm's proprietary owners hold stakes.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] There is potential for machine learning in health care to provide professionals with an additional tool to diagnose, medicate, and plan recovery paths for patients, but this requires these biases to be mitigated.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Since the 2010s, advances in both machine learning algorithms and computer hardware have led to more efficient methods for training deep neural networks (a particular narrow subdomain of machine learning) that contain many layers of nonlinear hidden units.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] By 2019, graphics processing units (GPUs), often with AI-specific enhancements, had displaced CPUs as the dominant method of training large-scale commercial cloud AI.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] OpenAI estimated the hardware compute used in the largest deep learning projects from AlexNet (2012) to AlphaZero (2017), and found a 300,000-fold increase in the amount of compute required, with a doubling-time trendline of 3.4 months.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Tensor Processing Units (TPUs) are specialised hardware accelerators developed by Google specifically for machine learning workloads.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Unlike general-purpose GPUs and FPGAs, TPUs are optimised for tensor computations, making them particularly efficient for deep learning tasks such as training and inference.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] They are widely used in Google Cloud AI services and large-scale machine learning models like Google's DeepMind AlphaFold and large language models.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] TPUs leverage matrix multiplication units and high-bandwidth memory to accelerate computations while maintaining energy efficiency.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Since their introduction in 2016, TPUs have become a key component of AI infrastructure, especially in cloud-based environments.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Neuromorphic computing refers to a class of computing systems designed to emulate the structure and functionality of biological neural networks.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] These systems may be implemented through software-based simulations on conventional hardware or through specialised hardware architectures.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] A physical neural network is a specific type of neuromorphic hardware that relies on electrically adjustable materials, such as memristors, to emulate the function of neural synapses.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] The term "physical neural network" highlights the use of physical hardware for computation, as opposed to software-based implementations.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] It broadly refers to artificial neural networks that use materials with adjustable resistance to replicate neural synapses.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning is a sub-field of machine learning where models are deployed on embedded systems with limited computing resources, such as wearable computers, edge devices and microcontrollers.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Running models directly on these devices eliminates the need to transfer and store data on cloud servers for further processing, thereby reducing the risk of data breaches, privacy leaks and theft of intellectual property, personal data and business secrets.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Embedded machine learning can be achieved through various techniques, such as hardware acceleration, approximate computing, and model optimization.
[src:aws-macie/machine-learning-p02] Common optimization techniques include pruning, quantisation, knowledge distillation, low-rank factorisation, network architecture search, and parameter sharing.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] In general, **compliance** means conforming to a rule, such as a specification, policy, standard or law.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Compliance has traditionally been explained by reference to deterrence theory, according to which punishing a behavior will decrease the violations both by the wrongdoer (specific deterrence) and by others (general deterrence).
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] This view has been supported by economic theory, which has framed punishment in terms of costs and has explained compliance in terms of a cost-benefit equilibrium (Becker 1968).
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] However, psychological research on motivation provides an alternative view: granting rewards (Deci, Koestner and Ryan, 1999) or imposing fines (Gneezy Rustichini 2000) for a certain behavior is a form of extrinsic motivation that weakens intrinsic motivation and ultimately undermines compliance.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Regulations and accrediting organizations vary among fields, with examples such as PCI-DSS and GLBA in the financial industry, FISMA for U.S. federal agencies, HACCP for the food and beverage industry, and the Joint Commission and HIPAA in healthcare.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] In some cases other compliance frameworks (such as COBIT) or even standards (NIST) inform on how to comply with regulations.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Some organizations keep compliance data—all data belonging or pertaining to the enterprise or included in the law, which can be used for the purpose of implementing or validating compliance—in a separate store for meeting reporting requirements.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Compliance software is increasingly being implemented to help companies manage their compliance data more efficiently.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] This store may include calculations, data transfers, and audit trails.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The ISO also produces international standards such as ISO/IEC 27002 to help organizations meet regulatory compliance with their security management and assurance best practices.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Some local or international specialized organizations such as the American Society of Mechanical Engineers (ASME) also develop standards and regulation codes.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] They thereby provide a wide range of rules and directives to ensure compliance of the products to safety, security or design standards.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance varies not only by industry but often by location.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The financial, research, and pharmaceutical regulatory structures in one country, for example, may be similar but with particularly different nuances in another country.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] These similarities and differences are often a product "of reactions to the changing objectives and requirements in different countries, industries, and policy contexts".
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] These regulators help to ensure financial institutes meet their promises, that transactional information is well documented, and that competition is fair while protecting consumers.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Australian organisations seeking to remain compliant with various regulations may turn to AS ISO 19600:2015 (which supersedes AS 3806-2006).
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] This standard helps organisations with compliance management, placing "emphasis on the organisational elements that are required to support compliance" while also recognizing the need for continual improvement.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] In Canada, federal regulation of deposits, insurance, and superannuation is governed by two independent bodies: the OSFI through the Bank Act, and FINTRAC, mandated by the Proceeds of Crime (Money Laundering) and Terrorist Financing Act, 2001 (PCMLTFA).
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] These groups protect consumers, regulate how risk is controlled and managed, and investigate illegal action such as money laundering and terrorist financing.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] On a provincial level, each province maintain individuals laws and agencies.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Unlike any other major federation, Canada does not have a securities regulatory authority at the federal government level.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The provincial and territorial regulators work together to coordinate and harmonize regulation of the Canadian capital markets through the Canadian Securities Administrators (CSA).
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Other key regulators in Canada include the Canadian Food Inspection Agency (CFIA) for food safety, animal health, and plant health; Health Canada for public health; and Environment and Climate Change Canada for environment and sustainable energy.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] For more industry specific guidance, e.g., financial institutions, Canada's E-13 Regulatory Compliance Management provides specific compliance risk management tactics.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Regulatory compliance in the European Union (EU) is governed by a harmonized legal framework designed to ensure consistency across member states while allowing for national implementation.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] EU compliance regulations cover various industries, including consumer product safety, financial services, environmental protection, and data privacy.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The General Product Safety Regulation (GPSR) establishes a unified safety framework for consumer products across the EU, requiring manufacturers to conduct risk assessments, maintain traceability documentation, and meet safety compliance standards before placing products on the market.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The GPSR applies to all consumer products made available in the EU unless covered by sector-specific regulations, such as medical devices or food products.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The regulation extends to products sold through e-commerce platforms, requiring online marketplaces to ensure that only compliant products are listed.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Fulfillment service providers are also included as economic operators, making them responsible for product safety compliance in certain cases.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] For business compliance, the EU’s regulatory approach is guided by the New Legislative Framework (NLF) and various sector-specific directives and regulations.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Businesses must comply with EU product conformity assessments and affix the CE marking to indicate compliance with essential safety and performance standards.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Financial compliance is enforced through regulations such as the Markets in Financial Instruments Directive (MiFID II) and the General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR), which set strict requirements for financial transparency, consumer protection, and data security.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The EU Legislation Compliance framework ensures that organizations operate within the legal boundaries of EU directives, helping public and private entities manage regulatory risks efficiently.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Companies operating in the EU must stay updated on evolving compliance requirements, as non-compliance can lead to fines, product recalls, or restrictions on market access.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The financial sector in the Netherlands is heavily regulated.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The Dutch Central Bank (De Nederlandsche Bank N.V.) is the prudential regulator while the Netherlands Authority for Financial Markets (AFM) is the regulator for behavioral supervision of financial institutions and markets.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] In India, compliance regulation takes place across three strata: Central, State, and Local regulation.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] India veers towards central regulation, especially of financial organizations and foreign funds.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Compliance regulations vary based on the industry segment in addition to the geographical mix.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Most regulation comes in the following broad categories: economic regulation, regulation in the public interest, and environmental regulation.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] India has also been characterized by poor compliance - reports suggest that only around 65% of companies are fully compliant to norms.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The Monetary Authority of Singapore is Singapore's central bank and financial regulatory authority.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] It administers the various statutes pertaining to money, banking, insurance, securities and the financial sector in general, as well as currency issuance.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] There is considerable regulation in the United Kingdom, some of which is derived from European Union legislation.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Various areas are policed by different bodies, such as the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA), Environment Agency, Scottish Environment Protection Agency, Information Commissioner's Office, Care Quality Commission, and others: see List of regulators in the United Kingdom.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Important compliance issues for all organizations large and small include the Data Protection Act 2018 and, for the public sector, Freedom of Information Act 2000.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Corporate scandals and breakdowns such as the Enron case of reputational risk in 2001 have increased calls for stronger compliance and regulations, particularly for publicly listed companies.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The Office of Foreign Assets Control (OFAC) is an agency of the United States Department of the Treasury under the auspices of the Under Secretary of the Treasury for Terrorism and Financial Intelligence.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] OFAC administers and enforces economic and trade sanctions based on U.S. foreign policy and national security goals against targeted foreign states, organizations, and individuals.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in the U.S. generally means compliance with laws and regulations.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] These laws and regulations can have criminal or civil penalties.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The definition of what constitutes an effective compliance plan has been elusive.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Most authors, however, continue to cite the guidance provided by the United States Sentencing Commission in Chapter 8 of the Federal Sentencing Guidelines.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Small Business Administration re-launched Business.gov (later Business.USA.gov and finally SBA.Gov) which provides a single point of access to government services and information that help businesses comply with government regulations.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Department of Labor, Occupational Health and Safety Administration (OSHA) was created by Congress to assure safe and healthful working conditions for working men and women by setting and enforcing standards and by providing training, outreach, education, and assistance.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] OSHA implements laws and regulations regularly in the following areas, construction, maritime, agriculture, and recordkeeping.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The United States Department of Transportation also has various laws and regulations requiring that prime contractors when bidding on federally funded projects engage in good faith effort compliance, meaning they must document their outreach to certified disadvantaged business enterprises.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Data retention is a part of regulatory compliance that is proving to be a challenge in many instances.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The security that comes from compliance with industry regulations can seem contrary to maintaining user privacy.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Data retention laws and regulations ask data owners and other service providers to retain extensive records of user activity beyond the time necessary for normal business operations.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] These requirements have been called into question by privacy rights advocates.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Compliance in this area is becoming very difficult.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Laws like the CAN-SPAM Act and Fair Credit Reporting Act in the U.S. require that businesses give people the right to be forgotten.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] In other words, they must remove individuals from marketing lists if it is requested, tell them when and why they might share personal information with a third party, or at least ask permission before sharing that data.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Now, with new laws coming out that demand longer data retention despite the individual’s desires, it can create some real difficulties.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Money laundering and terrorist financing pose significant threats to the integrity of the financial system and national security.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] To combat these threats, the EU has adopted a risk-based approach to Anti-Money Laundering and Combating the Financing of Terrorism (AML/CFT) that relies on cooperation and coordination between EU and national authorities.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] In this context, risk-based regulation refers to the approach of identifying and assessing potential risks of money laundering and terrorist financing and implementing regulatory measures proportional to those risks.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] However, the shared enforcement powers between EU and national authorities in the implementation and enforcement of AML/CFT regulations can create legal implications and challenges.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] The potential for inconsistent application of AML regulations across different jurisdictions can create regulatory arbitrage and undermine the effectiveness of AML efforts.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Additionally, a lack of clear and consistent legal frameworks defining the roles and responsibilities of EU and national authorities in AML enforcement can lead to situations where accountability is difficult to establish.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Corporate Governance Code (formerly the Combined Code) is issued by the Financial Reporting Council (FRC) and "sets standards of good practice in relation to board leadership and effectiveness, remuneration, accountability, and relations with shareholders".
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] All companies with a Premium Listing of equity shares in the U.K. are required under the Listing Rules to report on how they have applied the Combined Code in their annual report and accounts.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] It further demonstrates the relationship that subsists among shareholders, management, and the independent audit teams.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] Financial statements must be prepared using a particular set of rules and regulations hence the rationale behind allowing the companies to apply the provisions of company law, international financial reporting standards (IFRS), as well as the U.K. stock exchange rules as directed by the FCA.
[src:aws-macie/regulatory-compliance] It is also possible that shareholders may not understand the figures as presented in the various financial statements, hence it is critical that the board should provide notes on accounting policies as well as other explanatory notes to help them understand the report better.
